<Author>Okemosian
<Content>Sleek and pleasant with some quirks We stayed at the Skipper 8 nights for a combination conference/getaway. We found the staff quite accommodating and friendly and the hotel very pleasant. It does have a very minimalist decor but it grew on us. And the location is excellent. It's nice to be so close to the beach and some great beach-front restaurants, and to be fairly close to La Ramblas, etc. That said, we found a few things somewhat quirky, certainly the bathroom facilities. They don't supply kleenex (well, a teeny packet of tissues) or washcloths. They do offer combs and toothbrushes and other nice amenities. The shower was amusing - there is a 5-step instruction card to turning it on, which can be fun when you are seriously jetlagged. Likewise, the bathtub, outfitted with the same oh-so-sleek system, was a puzzle. We had to call down to the front desk to seek help with getting hot water. And in the end, it was not very hot - there is apparently some scald control built in, and I like my baths hot, but...And the shower leaked all over the floor each time, right into the toilet floor area. And the lighting, well, it makes you look positively cadaverous. The sink is trough-like and shallow, and the faucet controls reminded me of stick-shifts with no indicators. Much water was sprayed in all directions in trying to adjust them. It was all actually pretty humorous but I felt sorry for housekeeping, having to mop up so much water every day. So the bathroom was very sleek-looking but not the most functional/practical we've ever encountered.  The bed was very comfortable. The noise level for us was pretty high as we were closest to the hospital nearby. Sirens at night, but we got used to it. Maid service was just fine. We and many of the attendees we were with had repeated trouble with their room key cards failing. We swapped ours out for new ones about 4 times.   We ate only in the bar (not restaurant) area a couple times, and here's a tip - if you aren't interested in the five or so sandwiches etc. that they offer, just ask them to make up a plate of tapas. A much better deal, better food. For some very good and inxpensive sandwiches, soups, salads, just head to the beachfront - there's a very pleasant indoor/outdoor cafe/sandwich place nearish the casino (stay away from the casino, a rip-off) And there along the beachfront we also recommend Agua, a restaurant apparently quite popular with the locals. (Try the three-cheese risotto - to die for. )  The conference facilities were good and the free Internet on business pcs there was nice. Elevators were fast.  Having been in Barcelona only once, I probably would try somewhere else on a 2nd trip, if only to see something new, not because our stay at the AB Skipper was negative. It was very nice, on the whole. 
